animal.description: Nikki is a bit of a mystery when it comes to her breed.  We were told she is a Weimaraner mix, but other than her beautiful rich grey coat, it is hard to know for sure.  She was born May 17, 2019 and weighs only about 40 pounds.  Nikki loves attention but is a little timid with new people and situations.  She just needs a little time to feel secure.  Nikki needs an adult home as she is not used to children. She has been around other dogs her size and smaller.  I do not believe she has ever been around cats.  Nikki is highly intelligent and willing to learn, but she needs a loving home with someone who is patient and loving.  She will do best with a fenced yard to run and play under supervision.  According to her previous owner, she walks good on lead and is housebroken.  Nikki is spayed, up to date on vaccinations, heartworm negative, microchipped, and crate trained.  If Nikki looks like a perfect fit for you, please fill out an adoption application at humanesocietycitrus.com and for additional information contact Karron at choose2rescue@hotmail.com or at 352-586-9699.  The adoption donation for Nikki is $200.00

animal.description:
Drumroll, please!!! The moment you’ve all been waiting for has arrived... Sophia is officially ready for adoption!!! Get those apps in ASAP because this dog is a true GEM!
 
When we first saved Sophia from the shelter, she was (in medical terms) a hot mess. In addition to being completely emaciated and having an upper respiratory infection, she had SEVERE skin infections (both yeast and bacteria). Everywhere you touched there was scabs and pustules, and her skin was solid black and scaly-looking.  With the right medicine and a consistent, healthy diet, her skin has improved.
 
She is pure perfection - she’s completely potty trained, she’s quiet, calm, super gentle & submissive and incredibly sweet.  She doesn't let her age slow her down! She’s still bouncy & playful and has quite the zest for life! She will need to be on meds for life for her arthritis and will need to be on meds for the foreseeable future for her skin (anti-fungal and steroid) - so any prospective adopter has to be ok with this.
 
Sophia loves going outside, loves playing with small dogs, loves toys, and loves watching squirrels out the window. She is also cat-friendly.  She is very timid and will take a while to get comfortable so she needs a patient family who will give her the time and space to feel comfortable.






Thank you for your interest in one of our furry kids! Adopting from Releash Atlanta means you will adopt a dog that has been fully vaccinated, spayed/neutered and microchipped! Our adoption fee is $350

**We only adopt to families in/around Atlanta, Ga (about a 1-2 hour perimeter)**

We do not monitor our Petfinder email address so if you are interested in any of our dogs, please visit releashatlanta.com to either view more of their profile or to apply! If you have questions, please email adopt@releashatlanta.com 

Take a moment and like our Facebook Page for updates on our dogs and the first look at dogs coming into the program! www.facebook.com/releashatlanta

Thank you!!

Meet the sweet lady we call Sabrina! He birthed & cared for her puppies. They are all adopted & now it's her turn to have the spotlight. She is just a pup herself at just a little over a year old. Sabina is lanky. She won't grow much more but might fill out a little bit. She is a German Shepherd. Sabrina is in am amazing foster home. She is being taught about everyday things that city dwellers do. She is loving it! Sabrina hadn't been exposed to much. She is a little on the shy side but don't let that fool you, she comes around for snuggles very quickly! She is learning lots from her foster fur siblings, like house manners & outdoor potty & is doing famously! She likes to go on walks with her foster family. Sabrina is learning the a crate can be safe but it's taking her a bit to get there. She wants to be with her people, so we suggest a home that can leave her out in the home the majority of the time is best; a family that is home often. Sabrina is meeting children & has shown no aggression towards them. We aren't sure how she does with cats but we can cat test her for anyone with a cat.

Interested? Please visit https://dogsbydebin.com/adoption-application/ to complete our quick online adoption application. Sabrina's adoption fee is $225 & includes: Spay, vaccines, microchip, deworming. Thank you!

animal.description:
Meet Jack !!! Jack was rescued from a very overcrowded shelter in SC.  He and his sister were found wondering the streets.  Once at the shelter they were so frightened the hid in the back of the kennel trying so hard to disappear. So when asked if we could save them how could we say no.  The fearful dogs never get adopted.  Since coming to NY both Jack and his sister Jill have learned that not all people are bad.  Jill has been adopted but Jack is still waiting for his happily ever after. Jack is a little weary of people until he knows you are not going to hurt him then he is just a love.  He needs a patient owner that wants to take the time to show him the world is not a scary place and not everyone is going to hurt him..

Jack is a year old.  UTD on shots.  Neutered and microchipped.  If you would like to meet this beautiful little boy please go to our website www.snarrnortheast.org and fill out an application

IMPORTANT: This puppy has not yet been altered. For any dog or puppy that is not able to be spayed/neutered prior to adoption, SNARR requires a $125 deposit in addition to your adoption fee, as well as a signed Spay/Neuter Contract stating you will have this dog altered within 6 months of adoption. The $125 deposit will be returned once the contract has been fulfilled. 

**PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING**

If you are interested in adopting any of the puppies, our adoption fee is $495 ( puppies) $375 (adults) which includes transportation from the South and we do suggest putting a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choicej on your application if applying for a puppy with several littermates.

**Please understand that we are a volunteer based organization. While our volunteers try to answer all emails/questions as quickly as possible, below please find answers to some of our most frequently asked questions. We ask that you please read these FAQ's to see if your question has already been answered before emailing additional questions:

- If a dog or puppy is listed on Petfinder, they are still available. Please do not email asking if they are still available. If a dog or puppy is still listed, then we are still accepting applications :-) We do not go on a first come first serve basis, but on best fit for the family and most importantly, the puppy or dog.

- We are taking our best guess on breed and size when fully-grown (or already an adult), based on the puppy's/dog’s physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. We rarely are able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. 

- Our dogs/puppies are either at our Adoption Center in Brewster, NY, in foster care, or are adopted straight from transport. An application is necessary to meet any dog/puppy. Often, dogs and puppies are spoken for before they arrive. Many people feel more comfortable with a meet and greet which we completely understand and respect, however please know you are taking a chance of that puppy/dog getting adopted by someone else before hand.

- The way to start the process for any dog or puppy is by filling out an application. Applications for foster or adoption can be found at www.snarrnortheast.org and by clicking either adopt or foster from the main menu. If you fill out an application, please make sure you answer all the questions in as much detail as possible and that you receive a confirmation email, otherwise we did NOT receive it.

animal.description:
*INQUIRIES SENT THROUGH PETFINDER WILL NOT BE ANSWERED AS WE DO NOT HAVE THE MANPOWER TO RESPOND TO THEM. PLEASE COMPLETE OUR ADOPTION APPLICATION INSTEAD*

Meet Handsome Huck!
Huck-TX is in an IDOG foster home in Taylor, TX – 35 minutes outside of Austin. Please read ALL the information in his listing before applying for him. If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for him, please complete our adoption application at http://www.idogrescue.com/adoption_application (copy/paste the URL into your browser). If you have completed an application in the last 3 months and meet the requirements for his new home, you can email us at rescue@idogrescue.com and let us know you are interested in him.

We will review your application and let you know if you made our short list of applicants. We base our adoption decisions on what is in the best interest of our dogs. Please note our adoption policies are in place for the safety and welfare of our dogs - your understanding is appreciated.

We are all volunteers and have jobs, families, pets of our own to care for - we do the best that we can to get back to you in a timely manner. We believe in taking time to go through our thorough process to try to match the dog with the best fit for that dog. 

Our adoption process may take 2-4 weeks. 
•	You must be approved to adopt before we will schedule a meet and greet. 
•	We expect approved adopters to visit Huck in his foster home within a short period of time of being approved to adopt him. 
•	Our adoption process involves vet and personal reference checks, phone interviews, a home visit, an adoption contract and an adoption fee.

*AGE: 2 years (born January 2019)

*WEIGHT: 83 lbs.

*FENCE REQUIREMENT: A physical secure fence of at least 5' is required. No electronic fence or e-collar will be allowed as we feel this would not set him up for success.

*COAT TYPE: straighter moderate shedding hair coat similar to a Labrador. His new family should be prepared to brush his coat regularly and have him groomed every few months. This is approximately $100 per groom.

*ENERGY LEVEL:  Active, high energy. He must receive a minimum of 2-3 walks/runs a day. He wants to get out and run, whether this is as a running partner… playing fetch… taking walks.  

*DOGS: he loves other dogs but due to his size and strength he may be too much for some dogs. He is sweet guy and an in-your-face powerful linebacker kind of a guy.

*CATS: unknown. Due to his lack of exposure to cats we will not place him in a home with cats in order to set him up for success.
 
*KIDS: 14+ years old. Huck is a typical x-large Doodle and is easily excitable. He can accidentally knock you over trying to lick you and will put his paws on your shoulder. He can be mouthy trying to get your attention. We recommend a dog-savvy home with kids 14+ who are familiar with large dog behavior, not afraid of a large dog’s size and energy and are OK being jumped on and mouthed and may be accidentally knocked down.
 
*CAR:  Rides fine in a car.  
 
*CRATE:  yes but hasn’t been in crate in his foster home. He was crated in his first home when his owners left the home for brief periods of time. He would not enjoy being crated for long periods of time and would much rather be out and about and running and getting exercise. He enjoys being next to his family.
  
*HOUSE TRAINED: Yes! 

*LEASH:  Walks fine on a leash.  Given his large size and young age, we would recommend a harness to allow for more control in the event something interesting crosses his path.

Here's what Huck-TX’s foster parents had to say about him:

Huck AKA Huckleberry is a 2 year old male 86 lb. F1 Labradoodle who was surrendered to IDOG by his family. They loved him very much and surrendered him to IDOG due to the owner’s health issues. They wanted him to find an active home where he could get more exercise.

Huck is super sweet, loving and playful…he is a large lapdog at 83 lbs. and strong – think  linebacker. He will nudge you for love and attention. He is a loyal and affectionate co-worker and will lay at your feet after he gets his energy expended. 

He loves to play and snuggle! He aims to please his person.  He is a big dog and families that are familiar with or can appreciate this fact will find that he is absolutely an amazing dog.  He loves to play, loves people (lap dog, will come for affection and pets and generally wants to be in close proximity) and is very smart. He is a wonderful co-worker and does fine with voices on conference calls, doesn’t bark… but does need breaks to enjoy a little activity. 

He needs a house that has a fenced yard to ensure that he is getting the daily exercise he needs and craves. He also needs to be walked/run at least twice a day and throw in a few games of fetch and football and he is happy.  When he plays he has the cutest tigger bounce into downward dog – and he has the cutest personality.

He would do best with a family that enjoys having a big dog. A family that enjoys a lap dog and an active partner would be ideal.  Someone who is OK with dog hair on their clothes as he sheds similarly to a long-haired Lab.

Huck is well-behaved and listens to the commands he has learned. He will need continued training  - he is very sweet but a bit stubborn and it will take consistency. He needs to continue working on these issues: not jumping up on people, taking treats gently, and not using his mouth to grab you for attention. His jumping can be hard if a person is not ready or stabilized. He is a wonderful dog and his issues can be addressed with continued training.

 ****The type of home where we feel Huck would be most successful:*** 
-Family with experience with large energetic dogs who will commit to go through training with him to ensure he becomes the best dog
-Kids 14+ who are acclimated to living with large mouthy jumpy energetic dogs
-Fenced yard - privacy fence at least 5' high
-Family who is willing to ensure he gets his energy expended in the form of physical and mental exercise

Huck is neutered, up to date on vaccines, microchipped, house and crate trained. He is heartworm negative and on heartworm/flea and tick preventatives.

IDOG will hold a $150 refundable training deposit to encourage Huck’s new family to go through training with him to help him be successful in his new home. Since 2006, IDOG has been working with rescue dogs and we have found that when an adopted dog goes through training with its new family it strengthens their bond and gives the adopted dog more confidence and security. The training deposit will be refunded upon proof of training classes.

ADOPTION FEE: $375 + $150 refundable training deposit to be refunded upon proof of training classes

OUR ADOPTION FEES RANGE FROM $100 - $750 depending on the dog. The following is a general guide, but each dog is assessed individually. It currently costs IDOG an average of over $400 for basic vet, grooming, and foster care on each dog; that does not allow for the ones who get sick, need surgery, have special needs, or are heartworm positive.

ADOPTION FEES:
Under 6 months $550 and up
6 months to 2 years $450 and up
2 years - 4 years $350 and up
4 years + $100 and up
Special Needs fee/donation assessed on individual basis

TO APPLY FOR THIS DOG, PLEASE COMPLETE THE APPLICATION ON OUR WEBSITE:
http://www.idogrescue.com/adoption_application

Hi friends! Chopper here checking in, and well some guys just can’t catch a break in life, and I’m one of those guys. I was rescued in such an emaciated state I could barely hold my head up. I gained weight and went through patella surgery for my bad knee. I was awaiting clearance so I could have my second knee done when symptoms caused me to have an MRI. Sad to say I have a degenerative metabolic brain disease. This will greatly shorten my life. I am still searching for my happy ever until.. place where I will have love, soft couches, and good food until.. I don’t know how long I have, it can be months or years. I do seem to be holding steady right now. I am such a happy, loving and goofy guy. I am just praying my luck will change and I will be blessed with the bestest home ever? ?? Chopper

Gracie will come fully vetted which includes a dental. She will just need a low key home that can help her feel confident and safe. No apartments and no small kids please.

animal.description:
Meet Brock!

Brock was turned into BARC along with his sister Tina. The owner stated that with the difficulties of the pandemic, that he could not keep them even though he had had them since they were pups. When we heard this it broke our hearts knowing that they went from the only home they knew since they were puppies, to a scary windowless run in the shelter. The shelter staff said that Brock was friendly and well tempered. When we got there to see him, he just wiggled his bottom constantly and wanted pets and attention. While we had him out he met a pit bull that was walking by and he was great. He did not growl or bark, but just wiggled his bottom more and went up to greet the other dog. He rode great in the car to the doggy boarding facility where we took him, but a couple times just wanted to get in the driver's lap and get attention.

Brock is a big boy and weighs close to 100 pounds, but he is not overweight. Brock is just a big ball of sweetness. He's about 3 years old. When you look at Brock's pictures, you will notice some patches of bright white fur on him. We haven't had him checked out by our vet yet (he's going next week), but it looks like he has vitiligo. This is not a problem and will not affect him in any way, other than making him look unique. Please give this handsome, and unique looking, boy the home that he wants so bad - forever.

Tina has already landed a fabulous new home so now it's Brock's turn! Let's get him out of boarding and back into a home! Please complete an app at www.scoutshonor.org.

animal.description:
All of our animals are true rescues from the Native American reservations of the Four Corners area. This is an impoverished area where most dogs have typically only known life outdoors, so expect some adjustment time  to life in a home (although most adapt quickly to the comfort and safety of a home).
All puppies have limited training and will need an adopter who teaches them the correct way to interact with the world. Our “rez dogs”  are mixed breeds and we can never guarantee their heritage, so we say they “look like” or “have traits like”, to give our best estimates. But honestly, your guess is as good as ours! We can also only guess at what their weight will be when they are full grown. For this reason, we expect adopters to be flexible in their expectations of size and appearance when adopting a puppy. What we do know is that these animals are very smart, make wonderful companions, and are truly grateful and loyal to their rescuers

* Prior experience with large dogs, preferably with LGDs
* Securely fenced, large yard

• Residence within 150 miles of Hollister.  
 
Stunning Maya is an  85-pound,  2-year-old Great Pyrenees who thinks she is a lap dog.   Like many livestock guardians, Maya apprently had inadequate containment, got out, and was runnign stray.  She has been in foster long enough to gain back her weight, her trust, and her joie de vivre.  She never stopped loving people and other dogs.

Maya would like to be petted all the time, please -- don't stop!  She is playful and lively with other dogs, but after she's had her play date, she'd like to be left in peace so she can follow her people around, just in case they need help loading the dishes or making the beds.  She will not do well left home alone for hours every day; she wants to be with her people most of the time.  

Maya is  house trained, has excellent house manners, and is happy to sleep in a crate or on a dog bed.   

Great Pyrenees are livestock guardian dogs (LGDs), bred to work on their own in a field with their charges, be they newborn lambs or large livestock.  They are gentle, loving, loyal, and protective without being aggressive.   They guard primarily by showing their presence, sounding their deep bark,  and, if necessary, chasing predators away from their family.  Although they may masquerade as fluffy rugs, they are agile and fast and powerful when they need to be. Because LGDs are bred to patrol a very large (10-square-mile) area, strong, dig-proof, tall fencing is critical, as is a yard large enough for giant dogs to romp.  Likewise, LGDs  can never be off leash, as they WILL take off unexpectedly if they believe they need to check out a possible threat.  Even the most experienced trainers keep their LGDs securely fenced or leashed at all times!   

Some Pyrs are working dogs who live with their flocks.  Other are moresuited to being family pets.  Maya definnitely falls into the latter category.  

Maya is spirited, active, and graceful, but she does need assistance to jump (into an SUV, for example) because she has a congenital malformation of one knee.  She will likely develop arthritis early because of this issue.   
 
Maya has been spayed, vaccinated, and treated for parasites.  She has an implanted microchip.  A series of radiographs of her knee will be made available to her adopter. 

To view video clips of Maya, copy and paste these links into your browser, one at a time:

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING MAYA, please send email to

Lynxcat@comcast.net

to request an LGD application.  (Do not use the  "ASK ABOUT" button.) AFTER your application has been approved, we will set up an appointment for you to meet Maya and her foster parents in Hollister, CA under strict COVID guidelines. 

We always answer email if we receive it. We never ship dogs. If you can see this listing, MAYA IS available; please do not write to ask whether she is.

animal.description: Yogi is a very special dog! He has such expressive eyes and you can just feel his love coming through. He ADORES his people—quality time is definitely his love language—and he enjoys hanging out with his foster "brother" (our other dog) as well. He is very friendly and comfortable around other dogs but he isn't a big player—he is much more interested in the people! Yogi is not a fan of cats, however. He pulls on the leash but does pretty well on walks overall; however, he'd much rather play ball instead. Yogi is estimated to be about 10 years old, but he hardly realizes it. He'll chase a ball for as long as his long legs can last! We play about twice a day for 10-15 minutes at a time and that seems to be plenty of exercise for him. He is very well behaved overall and seems like a very well adjusted family dog. He loves to follow us around the house and "supervise" all the household chores. It seems clear that Yogi was raised in a home and knows the basic in's and out's of the pet dog life—he's housetrained, doesn't chew or destroy anything, can settle down and relax with us during family time, doesn't steal food even though he's tall enough, and is content to hang out on his bed in the laundry room when we leave the house. Yogi is also a fabulous home office coworker! He never barks and is happy and content to lie calmly and quietly next to me on his bed (we call it his desk) while I work. Yogi is such a fabulous companion that it's hard to imagine how he ended up in need of a forever home! If you're looking for a laid back companion to spend quality time with, Yogi is definitely your guy. He would love a home with a person who will adore him as much as he adores them.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Did I catch your eye? Learn more about me by reading my profile below; I just might be your new best friend! Apply on our website
(

https://www.healingheartsrescue.org/adopt

)

to

set up a private meeting or check below for my adoption event schedule.

Age: 9 months old

Weight: 47 lbs

Dog friendly: Unknown at the moment, but likely will figure it out with the right training.

Cat friendly: Unknown

Kid friendly: Yes

Potty trained: Yes

Crate trained: Yes

Hello! My name is Clyde. There's so much to learn about me, please read to the end :) I am from Missouri and have decided Minnesota is a great place to call home. I am a sweet boy and I can't wait to find my forever home.

I currently have two human brothers (11 and 6 years old) and one human sister (4 years old). I like to follow them around the house to see what they are doing. I have not messed with any of their toys that lay all over the floor. I love to take naps on my bed.

I strive to please, therefor an experienced dog owner would help me thrive! My ideal forever family will help me learn manners around other dogs.
We have been working on obedience training. I know 'sit' and am working on 'stay'. I am potty trained and crate trained. I sleep in my crate in the living room every night and go in it when my people leave the house.

I am learning how to play tug-of-war and fetch. I am starting to figure out that I can chew on bones. I love treats and will try to do anything you want me to to get one! I love my food and get really excited when I see it being poured into my dish. I enjoy people and like to greet them when they come into the house. I am not alarmed by the doorbell or knocking as I do not bark at either one. I aim to please my people and often look to them for reassurance.

Will you give me a chance?!

Adoption Fee: $295

INTERESTED IN MEETING ME?

If you'd like to arrange a private meeting or begin the adoption process, please fill out an adoption application by visiting

https://www.healingheartsrescue.org/adopt

**Note on breed and age determination:

Breed and age are often determined on appearance, our own knowledge, veterinarian advice, and/or information from the sending shelters or previous owners. Most of our adoptable dogs were previously stray dogs with little history, we can't be 100% sure of a dog's breed mix, and unless there is a specific date of birth listed, we can't be 100% sure of a dog's age. Additionally, our assessments of a dog's interactions with other dogs, cats, or children are based on OUR experiences. Your experience may differ.

ADOPTION FEE INCLUDES:

Wellness check

Spay/neuter (puppies adopted with required spay/neuter certificate)

Age appropriate vaccines - rabies as required by law and distemper combo or proof of positive titer test

Heartworm test if over 7 months of age

Fecal test and/or deworming for parasites

Microchip



~ Healing Hearts rescue will also provide dental procedures, bloodwork, surgeries, and/or any other additional vet work as needed while dogs are in our care.

~ Adoption fees are non-negotiable and fees are listed on the dog's profile

~ Adoption fees can be paid the following ways with the required sales tax (7.525%) added:

PayPal

Credit Card

Cash

WANT TO HELP SAVE MORE DOGS?

Healing Hearts Rescue is a nonprofit, foster-based rescue

located in the Twin Cities area of Minnesota

that is 100% funded through adoption fees and donations

. We are excited for you to join us on this mission to save the lives of dogs in need.

We believe every dog deserves to be loved as true members of a family and are committed to fulfilling that dream one dog at a time! Sign up to foster, volunteer or donate on our
website

Healing Hearts rescue will also provide dental procedures, bloodwork, surgeries, and/or any other additional vet work as needed while dogs are in our care.

Hi there!  My name is SAMMY.  What’s yours?  Nice to meet ya!  I am in Houston, TX.  If you live nearby or within driving distance, can you come to pick me up to go home with you?

A nice person came along and took me in and, now, I am ready to hit the road to your house!  Uh, make that “our” house, OK?  I definitely need a house with a fenced-in yard cuz I need room to run and romp and be safe!  The rescue requires (1) a fenced-in yard and (2) a vet history from a vet that you have used for a current or previous dog.

I am a Shih Tzu.  I am 3-years old and I weigh 20 pounds.  I have been neutered and am up to date on vaccines so I'm ready to go to my new home with YOU!!  Those funny-looking 2-legged creatures said I’m also microchipped – whatever THAT is.  At any rate, I am fully vetted.  Is that anything close to petted?  I love to be petted!  They say I'm precious.  Hmmm, Is my name Sammy or Precious?

Wanna hear some more good stuff about me?  OK, here goes.  I like ALL people and dogs.  I am sweet and playful.  I haven't been around children and I might very well be OK with them but let's hope for a home with just adults.  OK?

I need my own home.  I'm still young enough to have a good, long life with you taking care of me and I'll take care of YOU!

I like to take naps when I'm tired from playing.  I need  love, exercise and couch-sitting when we get tired!  Let's be a team, OK?

If you would like to take me home (and you know you do), please email doggydarlings12@gmail.com  and they can get me on my way to a new and loving home!  My adoption fee is $350 and includes my vetting, neutering, and a microchip.

animal.description:
George is the kindest, gentlest soul who has simply won our hearts! When George came into our care as a stray, he was understandably nervous and shy. As we have gotten to know George, he has shown what a true gem he is! Although he is a senior, there is a puppy-like curiosity about George that is so endearing. George has been thriving with positive reinforcement training. Thanks to lots of tasty treats, patience, and encouragement, he has already learned ''sit'' and ''high five'' - he gets so happy when you let him show off his skills! George is comfortable and easy-going with other dogs of all sizes and would do best in a home with other friendly, social dogs. In his foster home, he loves to play with all of the other dogs and he is wonderful with everyone from 4 pounds to 70 pounds! We don't believe that George has known a lot of kindness in his life, and he will need patience and understanding as he learns ''how to dog.'' George walks nicely on a leash and appears to be house trained. He loves to be in the house playing with toys or in a soft bed but also loves to walk and run outside! George needs a nurturing, patient family that will show him all about the good life and help him be his best self. We are sure that George will continue to bloom in a loving forever home!

George's ideal home would include:
- Other social, friendly dogs
- No cats please!
- A secure fenced in yard
- Allowing George to be an indoor dog
- No children under the age of 10 years old

animal.description:
Please read ALL of the bio as it has specific information regarding specifics & needs for this little cutie!!

Here are the facts about: Toto & Gizmo *BONDED PAIR*

Toto (14 year old, Black & Grey Schnoodle) & Gizmo (13 year old, white Lhasapoo) are just the sweetest little love sponges that want to be near you all of the time. They are a true bonded pair as they are always near one another & do one anothers face grooming. Gizmo is definitely the annoying little brother & Toto just goes with the flow. Gizmo will follow you everywhere & Toto just stares at you, awaiting the moment you sit down & he is invited up to be in his most favorite spot: your lap.

Toto is potty trained & Gizmo is as well but like any old man, he has accidents. A belly band will help keep clean up's easy peezy.

Need a security system? These two will let you know all about Stranger Danger & give you warnings. Even if they see a critter on tv, Gizmo will let you know. It's just the cutest. Due to their barking, they probably wouldn't be the best apartment/condo living buddies as your neighbors may not appreciate it.

animal.description:
FROSTY is a gorgeous, playful, friendly retriever mix young dog who is estimated around 2 years old. He’s a little under 50 lbs. He has some hearing loss, and is a little shy and nervous in new situations but is friendly to known people. He would do best with a structured home, fenced-in yard and planned quiet outings as he can get very stimulated. Older kids over 12 who are respectful of him should be fine, but probably not younger. He can be reactive behind a barrier, and we can educate any potential adopters on what that means for his perfect forever home. He's doing well with his foster's dogs but is not yet cat-tested. Frosty gets very anxious when left alone for long periods of time and doesn't do well with a crate, so a retired or work-from-home person would be ideal. Contact us for more details as we continue to get more information from our foster.

Adoption fee covers: all vetting to age (including deworming, deflea etc ), spay/neuter (to be done at 6-8 months of age if not already done and included in adoption fee,  free 30 days of pet insurance, 6 week obedience course (or reimbursement for positive-based classes), and lifetime support of rescue.

Please fill out an application here for consideration: Tinyurl.Com/appshdr

* During this COVID-19 crisis, we are essentially doing only virtual application processing and meetings are using social distancing practices. We will not have any open hours until further notice and doing meet and greets by appointment with the utmost caution for personal safety. We are not a shelter so there are NO DOGS AT THE SHOP unless we have open hours. All our dogs are in foster care and are available to be seen by appointment.

NOTE: If a dog is listed as Adoptable, he or she is still available at that time. Also, our adoption area is within a several hour radius of us in Rochester, NY (NOT including Canada - sorry!)

Good with cats:  Curious – Dog savvy cats
Good with kids:  Yes
Energy Level: Medium
Available for Adoption: 1/30/2021 (Currently accepting applications).
Applications need to be approved before a meet and greet will be set up for any Fetching Hearts Rescue dogs. 

Meet Glitter!  Everyone could use a little extra joy in the new year!  Glitter is just the dog to bring some extra happiness and spunk into your life! Miss Glitter is a good looking hound mix. At 4 years old, she is fully grown at 57 pounds. She is a shelter favorite and is very loving and considered super sweet.   Glitter is great with other dogs and children.  She will need a home with dog savvy cats as she is curious.  Glitter’s training is still in the process. She is working diligently on becoming house-trained. Training is an important part of a dog’s adjustment to a new home. It can be a process, but having patience is key. Because of her open, affectionate demeanor, Glitter will be a well-adjusted pup in no time! Bring her home and bring home the fun. This spunky fun-loving girl is sure to be your heart's desire.

If interested in Glitter, please email to inquire at: SCREENING.FETCHINGHEARTS@GMAIL.COM OR COPY LINK BELOW TO APPLY AND FILL OUT AN APPLICATION: https://www.fetchingheartsrescue.org/adoption-form-online
to fill out an application.

Unless otherwise indicated, all dogs adopted through Fetching Hearts have received the following before being available for adoption:

Thorough veterinary examination.

All routine annual vaccinations, including Rabies, DHLPP, Bordatella (Kennel Cough), Heartworm Test, Fecal Test, Deworming, Microchip, Flea and Tick Prevention and Heartworm Prevention.

Spay/Neuter.
All dogs are quarantined for two weeks outside of the shelter (puppies four weeks) to ensure they don't break with disease.

VETTING NOTE: Fetching Hearts Rescue completely vets our dogs thoroughly to the best of our knowledge based on communication with our Southern Vets. If anything is brought to our attention, we treat the dog. After adopting the dog, you will be responsible for following up with all vetting going forward.

HEARTWORM NOTE: Dogs who were treated for Heartworm can test positive up to 4-6 months after last treatment. All dogs are immediately put on Heartguard/Ivermectin following the treatment to kill the Heartworm larvae. All dogs should be re-tested after 5-6 months from the last Heartworm treatment.

animal.description:
Tucker Lee is a 15 yr old, 77 lb, neutered male Lab who was turned into the shelter "due to age". His fur is a rich dark black, a little longer, thick and lush and as he might have spent a lot of time outside. Hs eyes sparkle, and he seems to have a deep love for fur and human alike. 

Walking out to the yard and consistently in the yard, Tucker was a "man on a mission" almost "power walking" wherever he went, LOL.  And he frequently trotted around the yard and ran to visit  a dog in the adjoining yard. The daycare dogs barking and running in the distance were of great interest to him, even to the point of barking "to them" to start a conversation. 

Someone forgot to tell him he is 15 yrs old. He is happy, a big smiler, most of all a "schmoozerr" and a polite talker albeit it slightly hoarse.  And despite his bad hips, when he runs, he has nicely adjusted and seems to "glide" above the ground. 

Like a younger pup, Tucker really enjoys fetching and catching a ball. We stopped after a bit after noticing he was huffing and puffing and realizing he would play  as long as you were willing to throw the ball. 

Tuckler has such a magnetic personality and he hasn't finished living or giving yet. He is far too happy and engaged in life. An instant love, boy. And what a wonderful boy he is!

Thank you for your interest in adopting from Lab Rescue OK!

The FIRST STEP in the adoption process is to fill out a Adoption Application at www.labrescue.net.

Processing of a application usually takes 5-7 days. 

*** Labs are not placed on a first come, first approved basis. Placement is at the discretion of Lab Rescue OK, Inc ***

animal.description:
Diva is a 5 month  old American Staffordshire mix looking for her forever hone.  She is good with kids and other dogs. May do well with a dog savvy cat. She is a very happy puppy and is crate trained. She would love a fenced in yard and a dog friend to rim with.  If you would like to learn more about Diva, please complete an application and then reach out to Roxy@bigfluffydogs.com

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

Cadey is an 8 month old Pyr mix looking for her forever home.  She is a very happy girl and loves to play with other dogs as well as cd=cuddle with her humans.  Cadey had some surgery on her hip, but gets along well with just a little skip in her step.  Breed exoerience and fence required.  If you would like to learn more about Cadey, please complete an application and then reach out to Roxy@bigfluffydogs.com

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

animal.description:
CoCo is a gorgeous 3 year old squatty girl! While she is a scrumptious roly poly of delight and is crate trained and housebroken, she does need a more specific home. CoCo will do best as either an only dog or with a submissive older/calm male. If CoCo is placed into a home with another dog her ideal match would allow Coco to be the top dog, would match her play-style, and will take her cues. CoCo does not like cats and also prefers a quiet home as loud noises are not her cup of tea, for this reason we will not place her into a home with children. CoCo requires a fenced in yard. CoCo will need to continue training once adopted and her new family will be required to have a minimum of 2 training sessions with her trainer.

CoCo is great with her foster family and is a very loving dog! She is working on being the best girl she can be and to overcome her past! She is truly a special and unique gem of a dog!

If you are interested in adopting Coco, please fill out an application today!

animal.description: Howdy, folks. I'm Tex! I'm a 2 year old Terrier mix with personality for days. I take a little bit of time to warm up to men, but I am all about the ladies! ( HOW YOU DOIN?) I get along well with other dogs but I'm a bit intimidated by cats. I'm excellent on a leash and really enjoy walks. I'm doing really well with my house training, but occasionally I'll have an accident if you don't pay attention to my dancing cues. I like to be close to my people. I would do best in a home with older kids (8 and up). I used to be left outside 24/7 so it’s a relief to be an inside dog now. If you're looking for an all-around good boy, look no further than this scruffy face. I’m up to date on all my shots, heartworm negative, on heartworm preventative and flea preventative, neutered, microchipped, and de-wormed. Tex’s adoption fee is $325.

My foster parents figured out really quick that I love to be petted and told how handsome I am. My home before this wasn't the best, so when my foster parents and siblings try to play with me I get a little confused - I just don't know what to do yet, but I am learning. They keep saying I'm a genius because I learned how to sit the first day I was here, and I'm getting really good at laying down too. I take treats softly, am crate trained (but I'd rather be out with humans), and my foster parents think I am pretty much house trained. I would fit in well with almost any family, but if you have another dog to help me learn that would be great!

animal.description:
Introducing Tiggert!  This gorgeous male terrier is so very sweet and ready to find a loving home.  He is very gentle and a little shy in his new surroundings at our rescue.  As each day goes by, we see a little more of his outgoing personality and his tail is always wagging.  Tiggert loves attention and is excited to be near people.  He is good with other dogs and is potty trained.

The NAWS Dog Adoption Program operates as a rescue versus a shelter.  We believe in matching the right dog with the appropriate family based on each specific dog or family's needs.  To achieve this, we believe in spending the appropriate amount of time with each family to allow for enough interaction time with potential adopters.  This cannot be achieved if people stop by unexpectedly to meet our dogs.  Please e-mail Stacy at stacy@nawsus.org to setup a day or time to meet with one of our adoption counselors and our potential adoptees.  Thank you!

Payton is a typical beagle - he loves to be outdoors and using his nose to check things out.  He likes people and is very friendly, always eagerly greeting anyone that stops to meet him.  

The NAWS Dog Adoption Program operates as a rescue versus a shelter.  We believe in matching the right dog with the appropriate family based on each specific dog or family's needs.  To achieve this, we believe in spending the appropriate amount of time with each family to allow for enough interaction time with potential adopters.  This cannot be achieved if people stop by unexpectedly to meet our dogs. We are open intake, meaning we can not turn away animals from either county we serve. All adoption fees include age-appropriate vaccinations, flea treatment, deworming, and spay or neuter, microchip, and adoption packet. Fees: Dogs over 4 months old: $100 Puppies under 4 months: $125. Cats and Kittens are $75 ($65 without microchip). For your convenience you can fill out an adoption application for any of our current residents at www.moaspets.com. Join us on Facebook at https://www.facebook.com/moaspets. It's a great way to stay up to the minute on the furry 4 legged friends we have looking for a loving forever home. animal.description:
All of our animals are true rescues from the Native American reservations of the Four Corners area. This is an impoverished area where most dogs have typically only known life outdoors, so expect some adjustment time  to life in a home (although most adapt quickly to the comfort and safety of a home).
All puppies have limited training and will need an adopter who teaches them the correct way to interact with the world. Our “rez dogs”  are mixed breeds and we can never guarantee their heritage, so we say they “look like” or “have traits like”, to give our best estimates. But honestly, your guess is as good as ours! We can also only guess at what their weight will be when they are full grown. For this reason, we expect adopters to be flexible in their expectations of size and appearance when adopting a puppy. What we do know is that these animals are very smart, make wonderful companions, and are truly grateful and loyal to their rescuers!

animal.description: Jemison #7704 is a handsome 1.5 year-old male Black Mouth Cur mix. Jemison is sweet, friendly, smart, and calm. . He is house and crate trained. He knows the commands: sit, stay, lay down, crawl, search and shake.  He walks very well on leash and enjoys long walks and dog parks. . He has been in a home with a 12 year old and spent lots of time with his neighbor's 5 year old.  He  is calm around children. That said he is also energetic and playful and will need daily dedicated exercise, playtime and mental stimulation. A big fenced-in backyard would be great. He does like being with his people and can get anxious when they aren’t around; he did live with a cat and they got along great, so a cat or another pup friend may be good for him. He is being treated for Erlichia and is seeking an adopter who will continue LCAR’s provided treatment at no cost. He weighs 75 pounds and is full grown. This pup is microchipped. We believe you can always teach an ‘old’ dog new tricks, so we highly recommend continued obedience training for this smart pup; it stimulates the dog's mind and establishes a good dog/adopter relationship. This pup, like all pups, should be on heartworm preventative; an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure. If you are interested in adopting this dog, and are already approved to adopt through our organization, please contact dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with the pup’s name and ID number in the subject line. OTHERWISE, please submit an adoption application online: http://www.lastchanceanimalrescue.org/adoptus.html E-mail dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with questions. animal.description:
We adopt only in the Greater St. Louis Area.

1. Absolutely must have a securely fenced yard.
2. No children.
3. Must be an active family, walking/hiking.

Meet Curly Joe.  He's twice the corgi you'll ever want. Why? He is a Cardigan-Pembroke mix (2 times the corgi with merle coloration.) Three year old Curly Joe is a BIG guy (the Cardigan genes) with a BIG personality.  He loves to snuggle and kiss, but on his terms. He is awesome at communication, but needs a very dog savvy family that is compassionate enough to listen and observe his behavior in order to understand AND respect what he's feeling. Curly Joe LOVES to go for power walks, and would be a great hiking companion.  Daily exercise will surely help him to slim down, but he is also happy to play couch potato in between soccer games and his daily sniffy walk, allowing his people to get their work done.  He REQUIRES a fenced yard for those soccer games (Treibball anyone?).

During his foster stay, he played with many other dogs including Aussies and Corgis from young to old, girls and boys. Curly Joe met a parrot, and he visited a resident cat without problems.  He would love to have another dog brother or sister, but as long as his family is active, he could be happy as an only dog as well.  He does become lonely if he can't be near his people though (slight separation anxiety accompanied by the cutest, most soulful howl), so he would truly be happiest with a family where someone is home most of the time (work from home, active retired, multiple persons with alternating schedules).  Curly Joe would not be an appropriate companion for children and requires an adult only family.  Curly Joe is neutered and up to date on all vaccines. microchipped, and house/crate trained. He will need to continue on his diet. 

This bears repeating - Curly Joe REQUIRES a fenced yard and adult only family. Do not inquire if you do not meet these requirements. You will not receive a response. To make an inquiry about Curly Joe, please email claireelizabeth@petssecondchance.org .  Visit our website at www.petssecondchance.org for more information.

animal.description:
Juda is a female estimated to be 2-3 years old. She is spay, UTD on all vaccinations and preventatives. 

?Fence Required
?8+ years old min.
?Requirements must be met or app will NOT be processed.

Her foster mom writes the below about her: 

Juda is a petite in build dog who is energetic and likes to go where you do. She will shadow you where ever you go, if you allow her. She is getting accustomed to sleeping in the kennel at night but the first 20 minutes is her getting "comfortable" for the night as she may whine wanting to be next to her human as  she sleeps fine in the bed if you let her. She has not had any accidents in the house or kennel but she is not left to free roam the house when alone. Her routine is very simple which she seems to have down. In the morning she goes immediately outside from her kennel. She is very excited when she first comes out of the kennel and likes to express this by jumping, which we are working on her not doing. She is very good about going out and taking care of business and returning to the backdoor when she is ready to come in. She eats twice a day - morning and evening and enjoys her treats of eggs, pure coconut, and peanut butter bones. She enjoys playing with toys and tugawar. She has a buddy that is approx 1.5 - 2 yr old altered male who is taller than she but that do play very well together. She has shown no aggression towards the other dog and will take treats sitting next to him. They do eat at the same time but on opposite sides of the kitchen. 

Juda knows how to sit, speak, potty, come and we are working on kennel, sit and down (previously mentioned her jumping). 
She is a very loving dog and smart and would make a great companion. 

Until her jumping is under control, I would not suggest having her around small children for fear of knocking them over.

If you are interested in adopting Juda, please review our process, FAQs and the application. Link below:

https://www.battleforthebully.org/adoption

animal.description: PLEASE VISIT RESCUE DOG VILLAGE GUARDIAN, INC A 5013C NON-PROFIT ORGAINZATIONS WEBSITE AT WWW.RESCUEDOGVILLAGE.COM PETFINDER HAS MADE CHANGES TO FORMAT OF THE BIO, THEREORE; WE CAN NO LONGER PROVIDE LIVE LINKS TO THE APPLICATION OR AN EMAIL. WE ARE SO SORRY FOR THIS INCONVIENCE. APPLICATION: IF YOU WISH TO TYPE THE PATH TO OUR APPLICATION; YOU WILL NEED TO TYPE IN THE ADDRESS IN THE ADDRESS BAR. HERE IS THE ADDRESS: https://www.rescuedogvillage.com/adoption-application/ EMAIL: IF YOU WISH TO EMIAL RDV YOU WILL NEED TO OPEN YOUR EMAIL ACCOUNT AND TYPE IN THE ADDRESS For more information about this dog, email: ausman@gulftel.com PLEASE VISIT OUR WEBSITE RDV HAS LOTS OF PHOTOS LIVE LINKS TO THE APPLICATION AND AN EMAIL LINK FOR YOUR QUESTIONS. PLEASE NOTE EMAIL: you will need to open your email account and type in the address because live links have been removed by Petfinder APPLICATION: If this dog has stolen your heart, don't wait! Fill out an application https://www.rescuedogvillage.com/adoption-application/ to be considered as a potential forever home through our rescue. PLEASE NOTE APPLICATION: you will need to type the address in the address bar because live NAME: Kora GENDER: Female DOB: 06-07-19 WEIGHT: 53 lbs CHILDREN: 8 Years or Older BREED Rottweiler LOCATION: Bastrop, TX DONATION: $450.00 RESCUE DOG VILLAGE, RESCUE ME, ADOPT A PET & PETFINDER Meet Kora, an absolutely beautiful 4 year old, 58 pound Rottweiler mix. Clearly the predominant breed is Rottweiler, with that luxurious shiny black coat and pretty brown markings. Kora was rescued just in time from a kill shelter in TX. It is unclear why she was left there, and sadly, this happens very frequently. Too often a dog is dropped at a shelter because owners “just don’t have time” or “she doesn’t behave”, or simply because a puppy is a novelty and when the dog grows up it becomes a nuisance. The casualty is a pup that is ripped from the only home he or she ever knew. Whatever the case may be, Kora was extremely lucky and is currently with a loving foster family while she awaits her forever home. Kora’s foster family says she is super sweet but not needy. She loves her people, but is also perfectly happy laying in her bed chewing a bone. She is spayed, microchipped, heartworm negative, dewormed, flea/tick treated, and up to date on all her vaccines. Now all she needs is her own people to complete the package! Kora is very loyal, and would be a great family dog; likely with older children due to her size and breed. It is always recommended that young children are never left unsupervised with ANY dog. Children often love to be physical (ie: big bear hugs) with their new family members and rescue dogs can become nervous. We can never be very sure of what these pups have gone through. An adult-only home would be great for Kora as well. She is a true love bug with her humans and is very mellow, but likes to be “in charge” with other dogs, so being the only dog in the home would suit her well. Though “neediness” is a common trait in Rottweilers, Kora displays none of that so far. Kora seems to be fully house trained and her manners are very good. She will be very gentle with her fluffy bed in her kennel and is quite obliging when her humans dress her up. You can see by her pictures how patient (and pretty!) she looks! Kora is calm natured and loves walks. She walks great on the leash, and has shown no aggression at all towards other dogs from a distance while walking. While in her yard Kora only reacts to other dogs if they get too close to her fence. She absolutely LOVES car rides. Foster mom took her out for an afternoon and she jumped right in the car and laid down. She was great for the whole ride! The medical staff at the vet that cared for her said that she was a very easy and polite lady when they had to treat or examine her for anything. All the volunteers loved her! When choosing a new family member it is important to research the different breeds of dogs available to you. Personality traits, size, and temperament should all be key factors when deciding what pup will fit well in your family. The Rottweiler is one of the most popular dogs in the USA, UK, and Canada. For good reason, too, as this breed is a wonderful blend of the loving house-dog and the steadfast protector that will guard your home and your children. Not only that, but they’re relatively easy to manage within the home, as they don’t require vigorous exercise, and their intelligence makes them one of the easier dog breeds to train. Rottweilers are also relatively docile, and are willing to learn at the hand of someone they love (although it takes a bit to build that trust for this breed). The Rottweiler breed often gets a bad reputation. You’ve probably heard — in one way or another — that Rotties can be incredibly aggressive, downright mean, and off-putting to other people. While these traits can certainly be true, and are perhaps a bit worse when it comes with a dog powerful enough to do damage, these traits don’t apply to most Rottweilers. The true personality of a Rottweiler, and what they were bred to be, is a mixture of the loyal, steadfast watchdog, and the incredibly loving homebody. Also, despite popular belief, the Rottweiler is actually one of the most intelligent dog breeds in existence. Their ability to learn, adapt to their environments, and their keen eye for their surroundings are nearly unparalleled. Not only that, but they’re also well-rounded within the home. They’re patient and gentle with children, and the more they grow to know them, the stronger their protective nature becomes. Rottweilers are very cautious dogs, and people often see this as standoffishness or mean. This personality trait is rooted in their history. They’re extremely reserved when it comes to others infringing upon those they love, but that doesn’t mean they’re not friendly. They’re simply aware of the situation, and know how they must react if they’re called to action. The personality of a Rottweiler can also sometimes be considered needy. They love to be loved, and love to love, and often create a sense of dependency with their owners. Meaning these are not the dogs to own if you don’t have the proper time to be at home with them (or train them, as Rottweilers come with serious responsibility). Rottweilers, while dignified, confident, and powerful, are also extremely sensitive. All-in-all, these dogs are fantastic companions and will protect the household in earnest, will love abundantly, and are great additions to a home with youngsters. Another thing to note about their personality is that they’re fearless. If they’re called to action, or feel they need to protect those they love, they never hesitate. Kora has many of the typical Rottweiler characteristics and is protective of her family and the people she loves. It is part of the breed. She will need someone that can help show her that she doesn’t have to worry about protecting them. She needs to know when she should alert and when not to alert to situations. A family that is very familiar with this breed, or a similar one, would be ideal for Kora. She is on the right path and, so far, has been a model citizen, but training will need to continue. She is a delightful girl and will be a wonderful addition to the right family. Those who know Rotties will quickly realize Kora is a gem! Elan is a wonderful boy, and would make a fantastic addition to a family willing to continue his training and to love him unconditionally. He would thrive in a home with someone who is knowledgeable in these particular breeds or has experience with larger, active breeds. With structure and consistency, Elan would be an exceptional addition to an active family. Chase is 5 years old Rat Terrier Mix and he is currently in foster care so we have learned more about him.     He lost his home when his landlord said "no pets".  Chase is very polite, smart, obedient, and quiet. He walks very well on a leash.
He also grunts!  Chase gets along with other dogs in his foster home, but displays jealousy when they seek attention when he's on his foster mom's lap.
This behavior may pass as he becomes more confident.  He chases the resident cat, so a cat free home would be a better choice for him. He can be shy, yet a wonderful greeter at the door. 

No cats, no kids for Chase. 

Chase is  neutered, vaccinated (including bordetella) and microchipped.  His adoption fee is $215.00. (cash or check only, we are unable to accept credit cards)

Chase is kindly sponsored by Charlie Fisher, Chelsea Barber, Dan Courtine in honor of Holly and Xander, Suzanne and former NCCR residents, Tillie Mae and Bron Bron, and Rebecca Wood. Thank you!

If you think you might be interested in adopting, your first step should be to complete an adoption application. APPLICATION to ADOPT: Copy and paste this link in your browser to view and complete the application https://forms.gle/NghtT4WTNiaZu7Cg9. You can also select the link, right click and choose open in a new window.

We do adopt out of state, however we do not transport or ship dogs.  Potential adopter must be able and willing to travel to the Rescue to meet the dog they are interested in.  

*PLEASE double check all of the phone numbers that you provide as if they are incorrect, we will be unable to process your application.  Please also let your references know that someone from NCCR will be calling them. Most adoption team members call from their personal phone so advise your references that there may be an unknown number or a private number calling them.

animal.description:
Abigail is a 2 year old, Plot hound mix, who came in to rescue as the proud mama of 7 babies. Now that her puppies have found their own homes, it's Abigail's turn! Abigail is only about 30 lbs, and she can be shy at first. However, don't let that stop you, because once she gets to know you, she will become your best friend. Abigail's favorite hobbies are rolling around in the leaves, and following her foster parents around the house. She is currently fostered with both cats and dogs, and does great with both, but mostly spends her time with the humans. Abigail is crate trained and house broken, and will make an excellent addition to anyone's home. Her adoption fee is $250.00.

To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Shadow (TX) is a male Golden Retriever mix rescued in Texas. Our veterinary partner estimates that Shadow is 5 years old at the time of intake in December 2020. Shadow is good with people of all ages and other dogs, but no cats for this guy! Poor Shadow was living life as a stray on the dangerous streets of Texas, and he was barely surviving. When Shadow was rescued from the streets, he was suffering from severe hair loss, he was extremely emaciated, flea infested and anemic. We took him immediately to our veterinary partner where he received the medical care he required and now Shadow is ready to move on to his happy life. Shadow has a typical Retriever disposition--loving and mischievious--and he needs some work on basic commands! Shadow is looking for a home where he will be safe and loved for the rest of his life, and because forever means forever, he will never be homeless again. If you can give Shadow that life, please apply online to adopt Shadow (TX) at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

Good with cats:  No
Good with kids:  Yes

Applications need to be approved before a meet and greet will be set up for any Fetching Hearts Rescue dogs. 

Meet Rudy! This guy has an awesome personality. Rudy is a hound mix who is currently around 10 months old and weighs around 67 pounds and he still has a bit of growing to do. Rudy is a sweet boy with an amazing attitude for life. He enjoys spending time with other dogs and children too. Rudy will chase after cats, so a kitty free home is a must. He is in the process of crate training, walking nicely on a leash and house training. Rudy aims to please, so with treats and lots of positive attention, he is sure to continue to work on all the skills needed to be a good boy! This fellow will thrive in a home where attention can be given to him to help him continue to be an amazing lifelong companion. The perfect owner(s) will have a soft dog bed, lots of toys and time for belly pats and ear rubs! Rudy is a sweet boy with lots of love to give. He can’t wait to have his own unique family to call his own!

If interested in Rudy, please email to inquire at: SCREENING.FETCHINGHEARTS@GMAIL.COM OR COPY LINK BELOW TO APPLY AND FILL OUT AN APPLICATION: https://www.fetchingheartsrescue.org/adoption-form-online
to fill out an application.

Unless otherwise indicated, all dogs adopted through Fetching Hearts have received the following before being available for adoption:

Thorough veterinary examination.

All routine annual vaccinations, including Rabies, DHLPP, Bordatella (Kennel Cough), Heartworm Test, Fecal Test, Deworming, Microchip, Flea and Tick Prevention and Heartworm Prevention.

Spay/Neuter.
All dogs are quarantined for two weeks outside of the shelter (puppies four weeks) to ensure they don't break with disease.

VETTING NOTE: Fetching Hearts Rescue completely vets our dogs thoroughly to the best of our knowledge based on communication with our Southern Vets. If anything is brought to our attention, we treat the dog. After adopting the dog, you will be responsible for following up with all vetting going forward.

HEARTWORM NOTE: Dogs who were treated for Heartworm can test positive up to 4-6 months after last treatment. All dogs are immediately put on Heartguard/Ivermectin following the treatment to kill the Heartworm larvae. All dogs should be re-tested after 5-6 months from the last Heartworm treatment.

animal.description:
Hi, I’m Jodi!

My mom was a Golden, and my dad was probably a greyhound – as you can see, I am all legs! I’m just about 6 months old, so I still have some growing to do.
I am a very sweet and gentle puppy. I walk great on the leash and take treats very gently. I like to go on walks and car rides. I like people and other dogs, and I’d love to have a dog buddy in my forever home. I’d be good with a calm cat as well. I am usually quiet but will let you know if I see or hear someone coming up to the house.

I do have some puppy habits. I like to chew things that aren’t mine, like shoes. I will drop them when asked, though, and can be redirected to my own toys. I also still worry about if I’m going to get my next meal, so I can be possessive about my food and treats and I am nervous when I eat. My foster parents have been working on that by giving me really yummy treats when I’m eating or chewing on a toy and I’m learning really quickly that having people around my food and toys is a good thing. Since I’m still a puppy, I need to make frequent trips outside to use the bathroom. I also like to be around my people all the time. I will need some training to be independent.

I am super calm and laid-back in the house. I love to do zoomies outside, though, and I am really fast! So I’d love a big yard or trips to the dog park. I’d also probably make a great running partner, especially since I am so good on the leash! And then I will be so happy to cuddle up with you on the couch. I am such a cool dog!


If you're interested in meeting Jodi or in learning more about her, please contact Golden Bond Rescue at info@goldenbondrescue.com.

Adoption Fee: $1200 + $35 microchip fee
 

* * * * * * * * * *
Evie is being fostered in Milwaukie, Oregon

PACIFIC NORTHWEST APPLICANTS ONLY: Oregon, Washington, Idaho, Northern California and Southern British Columbia. Please do not inquire if outside these areas.

Golden Bond DOES NOT adopt to families with children under 10. Home ownership and secure 5-foot fencing is required.

See our website, www.goldenbondrescue.com for more information.

animal.description:
Hi, I’m Denny! I’m a cute smaller Shepard/Pit mix that is about 6 years old. While I am about 6 years old, I still look young and have the energy of a pup! You see, Chain of Hope has been a part of my story for a long time and finally, after a lot of time on a chain outside and a month at KCPP, I’m here! Since my life has been a little rough, it took me time to warm up but now, I’m beginning to trust people. I love to play and absolutely love sausage biscuits, peanut butter, and squirt cheese. animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email US at ctjja4palm@gmail.com
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Lucy
Estimated Breed : Hound Mix
Approximate Age: 2-4 years
Approximate Weight: 75 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Lucy is a beautiful, sweet and gentle momma who is waiting to find a loving forever home. She has been a wonderful momma to her litter of 10 puppies, and now it's time for her to find her own forever family. She knows some commands, takes treats very gently, and LOVES to play fetch and go for a ride in the car. Lucy is good with kids. Lucy prefers to be an only dog, but would do well with another calm housemate. Please consider opening your heart and home to this sweet girl.
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
I am the happiest Baby, the sweetest Baby, the silliest Baby, and the cutest Baby you will ever meet! Have you seen my ears? I’m adorable! I am suuuuuper excited to meet new people and new dogs, I love everyone and everything… well, except cats. That’s why my mommy has to help me find a new home, too many cats in the house for me, and I have a high prey drive when it comes to cats. This is something my new family needs to have experience with. I’m super smart and know a ton of commands and even some tricks! I’ve started agility training and looooooooove it! I need to be in a dog-savvy home that is active and it must be a home that will continue to work with me on my skills and take me to classes since I’m such a smart baby! I love my toys and playing with my mommy or other dogs and am great on the leash! My mommy walks me on a hands-free leash, that’s how good I am! I’m working on potty training; I’m good at telling my mommy when I need to go outside to go pee and can hold my bladder in the house for a few hours without any problems. I sleep through the whole night in my crate without any accidents. And while I’m an active puppy, I also love to cuddle and watch TV in the evenings; my favorite place is a lap, I love to curl up in a ball on my mommy’s lap and snuggle for hours. I would love to live with other dogs and would also be completely happy as an only dog since I’m so attached to people. I would also love to be your Baby! Want to meet me so I can give you kisses?

If you are interested in meeting this pooch, please download the Adoption Questionnaire (farescue.org/pdf_files/questionnaire_canine.pdf), fill it out and email it back to us at info@farescue.org or fax (310) 362-0321. You can also meet this and/or other available dogs at our weekend adoptions.

[Baby is about 5 months old and weighs 35 lbs.]

animal.description:
NOTE: NICHOLAS AND CINDY LOU ARE A BONDED PAIR AND MUST BE ADOPTED TOGETHER.

NICHOLAS is a loving, 1-year-old, 37-pound (very underweight), Hound mix. This young dog came to AA, the casualty of a cruelty case. He arrived with his companion Cindy Lou. Both dogs had been left outside in the freezing cold temperatures to starve. When the animal control officer went to the residence to remove the pair, he found Nicholas curled up around Cindy Lou trying to keep her warm. They are both very sweet, lovable young dogs who have suffered greatly at the hands of heartless, cruel individuals. Better photos and more information on the way. Link to CINDY LOU's Bio: https://www.petfinder.com/dog/cindy-lou-50355434/nj/lambertville/animal-alliance-nj290/ WHAT'S NEXT? If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY! Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date! *** This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives. Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. BY APPOINTMENT ONLY: Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins). An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals. Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please). This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times. Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details. To fill out an adoption application, go to: https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/
