animal.description:
Max 1 year old neutered male Border Collie 40 to 45 pounds.

The fine print. RAWL adopts by application process not first come first serve. We are operating on an appointment system due to Covid-19. Once approved a appointment will be arranged. The application can be found on the RAWL website www.rawldogs.org  if you have questions please email inforawldogs@gmail.com or by calling 540-937-3336 between the hours of 7:30-1 (except Wed & Sun)


Max came to RAWL as a transfer from one of our shelter partners. His history before that is unknown.

I will be blunt. Max will not be homed to apartments, condo's, townhouses or a suburbia.  He is a working dog that requires the knowledge of a previous working or herding breed dog owner. He requires thinking exercise not mindless running for miles. It only turns him into a marathon runner. If he is challenged and worked using his brain he is happy and settled. He will not be placed in a home with children under 12. 


With the above stated. The good about Max. He is smart, fun and high pecking order. He is easy to train but will also test to see if you really mean it. He is loyal and respectful of those who he deems worthy. He is affectionate. His brain is on and ready to do something. He would be incredible at agility. 

He is not dog aggressive but is dog dominant. His toys are his toys he does not want to share them with other dogs. He does drop his toys on command for his handler. He knows sit, down and paw. 

If you have had Border Collies or the like you will appreciate his temperament. I personally find him to be a quick study who wants to learn and to keep learning.

animal.description:
Back in September this stray dog was roaming Highland Indiana. Then, roaming Hessville in November. She finally settled down in a quiet neighborhood of Hammond where she stayed for 4 weeks. All the neighbors fed her and watched for her as she aimlessly roamed the streets, just surviving. Animal Control finally got her to safety where she was warm, fed, and getting petted daily. 
Lets keep this part short..... young boy walks in to animal control and insists on "that one". Suddenly this wandering homeless canine has a collar on, endless conversations to listen to, and a christmas tree to wake up to in the mornings. She is here with us, at 2x2 Rescue, learning to be a functioning family member. 2021 will be her best year yet. . . . we promised that to her. She now plays, loves other pets, and is learning leash manners. Wander will take a little longer to settle in to a new home than a "normal dog" would but she is beyond worth it!
52 pounds, 4 years old Australian Kelpie

animal.description:
Welcome to the adoption floor Miss Jaylah. Jaylah came to us from another animal shelter where a new change of scenery and pace has helped her settle down. This girl will melt your heart and tug at your heartstrings. She is in search of her Valentine forever to be. 

Jaylah is a German Shorthaired Pointer Mix weighing in at #56 lbs. We estimate her to be about a year old. She was just recently spayed, current on basic vaccines as well has having flea/tick preventative. She also has had standard worming. 

Now that Jay Jay has started to come out of her shell and started to trust us at the shelter she has such personality. She loves to go for walks, play with her fuzzy unicorn.  She runs up and down the hall chasing it while playing fetch.  We are teaching her basic commands. She gets so excited she likes to jump up on people (not harshly) but she is learning that its good to keep all four paws on the floor.  She seems to enjoy the company of dogs her size but doesn't seem to care for anything smaller then she is. She walks well on a leash and has great kennel housetraining manners. Kitties she very focal on and wants to give chase too.  Kids, she hasn't been introduced to as of yet but we think children 8 years and older would be great for her.  Not because she is mean but she has a lot of energy and might bump a toddler down. This girl would make a great family dog who really enjoys the outdoors walking, hiking, or even cuddle time on the couch.  She just looks for anyone to give her attention. She has the sweetest soulful eyes that just makes our hearts leap. Please consider this girl. You wont be sorry. 

If you think you have the right home for this girl please fill out a dog adoption application and send it back to us. You can give us a call if you need help with answering any of your questions you may have. You will need to set up a time for a meet and greet. (607-739-3945)

http://www.horseheadscommunityanimalshelter.com

Ps. Pictures don't do her justice. She is a busy body and just loves to explore everything.

animal.description:
Titan is a very handsome 2 year old Alaskan Malamute and possibly husky mix.  This sweet and very affectionate boy was given up by his family who could longer care for him.  Titan is an active, playful and very loving dog who will instantly steal your heart at first meeting.   Being a big strong boy at 80 pounds,  we would not recommend small children, he does not realize his size and would love to be a lap dog!  Titan loves attention and will quickly get attached to a new family and person.  He will definitely need to spend most of his time in a cool air conditioned home and must have a fenced yard for playtime.  Titan has a wonderful personality and will be a great addition to a loving family or person.  He will be an amazing loyal companion and best friend.
Titan has been neutered, is up to date on vaccinations, tested negative for heartworms and is on monthly prevention.  He will be microchipped prior to adoption.
For information on our adoption process and to complete an application, please visit allaboutdogscr.com or contact us by email at allaboutdogscr@gmail.com

animal.description:
Preston 1 year old neutered male Plott Hound approx. 55-60 pounds

Rawl adopts our dogs by application and appointment only. For an application please visit the RAWL website at www.rawldogs.org.  If you have questions about Preston or the adoption process please email inforawldogs@gmail.com or by calling RAWL from 7:30 until 1:00 (except Wed. & Sun)


Preston came to RAWL as a stray with a tracking collar. His owner opted not to reclaim him. He is all about being a puppy and would do well with someone willing to invest the time he needs for more training. He is housebroken, great on a leash and knows sit and paw. He is high energy with other dogs but will respect dominant dogs whom we've paired him with at RAWL to teach him manners. Preston went to a home with children on a trial and it was a huge fail. He is not able to comprehend on his own that  food and toys that are being held by the kids do not belong to him. For this reason no kids under 12.  

The great about Preston is he has a really good heart and tries. He just needs some direction in his life, which he is receiving at RAWL.  He cannot go to a home that expects him to learn on his own.  Obviously, a fence is required. He's a hound and wants to do what hounds do...use their noses.

animal.description:
New girl on the block.  Cheach, a senior Chihuahua.  She is in foster care right now and we have asked her foster mom to write up a short bio on her.  Here it is.
Cheach recently came into rescue when her elderly mom could no longer take care of her. She was quite stressed so it took her a few days to settle in.  She’s a very sweet 13 year old Chihuahua. I’m beginning to see her personality come out as she feels more at home. 
She seems to be pretty alert and healthy but she is overweight and needs to be on a good diet, but not too much! She’s missing many teeth and when she has her dental cleaning, she will probably lose a few more. Which is probably why so far, she won’t eat hard dry kibble. She is now eating well, Pure Vita, kibble soaked to soften, and mixed with canned food.  She is quiet and calm. She loves being outside and roams the yard until I call her in. She comes when she’s called, She is shy but will let me pet her slowly and carefully. That may be because I’m a new human for her. She gets along with the other dogs and has not chased the cat. Every time I let her outside she quickly does her business and has had no accidents in the house. She follows me wherever I go, even to the bathroom!.  What more could a family ask for!!
I think she will make someone a great companion. 
If you are interested in Cheach, please contact salemdogs@aol.com  and tell us about yourself, family, home, yard, fence, other pets, work situation, vet reference, etc.  We want to make a great match.  Please share this post and help us get this little critter into her new home.

animal.description:
Friends for life, Bear and Pippin are two tiny precious Chihuahuas that need to be adopted as a pair.  They are rarely apart and provide each other immeasurable comfort and companionship.  Both would be wonderful pets for a senior or family with older children.  No small children or puppies, please.  They prefer a calm quiet household where they can take a nap in peace.  Preferably, with someone that is home most of the day.  They like to follow you around the house as you go about your day.  Bear is a feisty five year old boy with a chocolate and white colored coat.  He may only weigh six pounds, but he’s definitely the boss and has a big personality.  His shy girlfriend Pippin is seven years old and a bit on the chunky side at eight pounds.  She’s a tricolored beauty and very calm and sweet.  With daily walks, Pippin should be fit and trim in no time.  Both dogs walk well on leash and enjoy taking trips to the park.  Like most Chihuahuas, they can be selective when making friends with other dogs.  If own a dog currently, we would be happy to schedule a meet and greet to check compatibility.  They are not fond of cats.  The perfect house guests, Bear and Pippin are very well mannered and already housebroken.  A fenced in yard is a must for these two tiny pups to keep them safe when outside.  Bear and Pippin are easy to love and care for.  If you are looking for a package deal, please consider this sweet pair.  

To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

Please read entire description.

RAWL is operating our shelter on an appointment basis due to covid. 

Our adoption process is by application and not first come first serve. The application can be found on the RAWL website www.rawldogs.org

Questions can be emailed to inforawldogs@gmail.com or by calling 540-937-3336 during the hours of 7:30 to 1:00.


Zeus 4 year old neutered male Shepherd possibly with Rottweiler.

Background: Zeus was transferred from one of our shelter partners. He was surrendered by his owner due to the new chaining dog law's in Virginia . Zeus lived his life on a chain. And despite  that he is an incredibility sweet dog that wants to please. He was a professional puller on the leash but took right to obedience and is now subtle and steady on the leash at a heel he will also sit and down.  He will only be placed in a home with a fenced yard where he can enjoy the freedom off leash. He can display some prey drive with moving objects such as cars. But can also be easily redirected to heel.  Zeus enjoys walks, playing ball and sunning himself.  He seems to be housebroken and has never had an accident in his run. (our dogs are let out from potty breaks and play from 6 am until 1pm and 6:30 pm until 10:00 pm )  Zeus shows too much interest in moving cats a home without them is best. He loves to meet other dogs but due to his former life can be a tad rude and some dogs are offended by his fast "hello". A home with a confident female dog would work well.

animal.description:
If you were to look up the definition of fun in the dictionary, Arlene's picture would be right there beside it! While some dogs take time to warm up to the hustle and bustle of the farm, Arlene seems to live for it! She has had a ball running around the fields and making new canine and human friends. She loves to play a game of chase and wrestle with her pals, but when a volunteer calls she comes running, eager to give and receive all the love! Arlene would do best in a home with older or no children as sometimes her excitement gets the best of our 60 lbs girl and she jumps and mouths to play. Like any teenager, at only 1-2 years old with likely no formal training all she needs is just a bit of guidance and structure to learn those aren't proper manners for a lady like herself. Arlene would love to find an active home, maybe even with a canine pal to be a furever playmate! Her fun-loving personality will be sure to enhance the life of the lucky home that decides to call her their own!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

Meet Tulip

Tulip became a Royal dog when she arrived from a rural area animal control that did no vetting. When she arrived we were pretty sure she was expecting. She had 2 beautiful babies and has done amazing in her foster home. Here is what her foster has to say about her.

Hi! My name is Tulip and I'm looking for my perfect family! I am told I'm one of the sweetest, kindest, lovable and patient dogs that anyone has ever met! I enjoy being outside, ESPECIALLY for walks or hikes, being in the leaves is my ultimate happy place! My foster family thinks I'd make a great hunting companion because I have excellent hearing and I'm very still when I hear something. I love cuddles and lounging on warm cozy blankets. I also LOVE kids and people in general. I'm very laid back and I just go with the flow. I'm not territorial over my food or my puppies. I'm housebroken but need some help with basic commands and not pulling on a leash, I am strong! I am not a huge fan of car rides, but if I can sit on your lap, I'm fine! For all that I've been through I think I'm a really good girl and so does my foster family! I'm also a huge favorite at RAR! Interested in meeting Tulip?

Apply at

animal.description:
Yogi and Bear are on their way and will be available to meet Monday, Feb 1st. Please apply online.
Yogi is 4.5 yrs old, and weighs 16 lbs. 
Bear is 12.5 yrs old and weighs 60 lbs.
Adoption Coordinator:  LK

No, it’s not a mistake.  Bear, the Golden Mix and Yogi, the Chi mix, are a bonded pair so if you couldn’t decide between adopting a Chihuahua or a Golden Retriever, here is your chance to have both.  Yogi is 5 years old and weighs 16 pounds.  Yogi has medium energy and is a little unsure of himself but as long as he has Bear by his side, he is braver.  He is learning that being picked up and cuddled by people is what people do with little pups.  He allows himself to be handled but always seems surprised.  Yogi loves bouncy balls because Bear loves bouncy balls and Yogi loves Bear.  They are good around other dogs and children but have not been around cats so a cat free home would be best.  Bear love to snuggle in big, soft, fluffy beds and Yogi loves using Bear as his big fluffy bed. They are crate trained and should be crated together as Yogi needs Bear to be his pillow.  It is also Yogi’s job to keep Bear clean and will groom him like a cat.  Yogi has a stiff leg but that doesn’t stop him from anything.  Yogi and Bear are a bonded pair and must be adopted together.  The adoption fee for the pair is $500. 

Please complete an online APPLICATION if you wish to adopt.  Forever Home Rescue New England is a 501(c)3  non-profit organization. We are a network of foster homes in the South and the New England area. THERE IS NO SPECIFIC SHELTER LOCATION. If you wish to meet our dogs, you must first be approved by going through our application and screening process. Forever Home Rescue suggests obedience training for all puppies and dogs. All dogs are up to date on their shots, dewormed and spayed or neutered. Vet fees, transport fee and New England quarantine fees ARE INCLUDED in each dog's adoption fee. Also, any dogs older than pups--even if they are not marked housetrained in their posting---usually housetrain within a day or two, because most are used to living outside in the south and will prefer to do their business outdoors. Our dogs and pups are best suited for families with children 5 yrs old and up. If you are approved to adopt, please submit the $100 deposit by clicking on our rescue's name in this posting (Forever Home Rescue New England--in purple) which will bring you to a new page with the deposit link at the bottom.  STOP! If you have not been notified of your approval status do not make a deposit.

Dolly showed up as a stray at someone's doorstep in Texas.  We think she is about 9-12 months. Still puppy. Loves to play and she will need plenty of chew toys available.

She has been introduced to cats but gets fixated on them, so would probably do best in a cat free home; or will require professional training to learn to leave them alone.

Dolly cannot be free fed, as she will likely overeat.

With lots of love and a little training, Dolly is going to be one fantastic dog!

animal.description:
Meet Sasha!  Sasha came to us (her foster family) about 5 months ago.  We do not know a lot about her past except she was definitely neglected and abused.  She and another dog were dumped at a small rural southern shelter; her companion was in such bad shape that she was immediately euthanized. When Sasha first came to our foster home in MN, she was terrified of practically everything and she found her safe place under a bed and refused to come out.  Her behavior was similar to what puppy mill dogs are like. It took about 3-4 weeks of the foster crawling under the bed with a leash to get her to go outside to the bathroom.  The foster had to feed Sasha under the bed as well and mix her food with a lot of water to make sure she stayed hydrated.  We are happy to say a lot of these behaviors have improved.

Throughout the last few months, Sasha has had a lot of ups and downs. The longer she has been with her foster she continues to have more ups.  She still spends the majority of her time under a bed (she now goes between 2 beds).  However, she now goes outside when the foster calls her name and runs outside with the rest of the dogs.  She eats without issues and has discovered a love of pizza and meaty treats.  She actually comes and stands in the hallway waiting to have treats rolled towards her.  She has braved the top of the bed quite a few times and at night will sleep on the floor next to the bed instead of under it. The times she has come up on the bed, she enjoys having the top of her head scratched and her belly rubbed.

Sasha is a beautiful 4-5 yr old Great Pyrenees / Australian Shepherd mix who weighs about 70 pounds.  She has white fur that is slightly coarse with spots of gray and caramel that are super soft.  She does fine with being brushed.  She has one quirky ear that stands up and one ear that folds over all the time.  She has this look of expectation that makes you want to hop up and give her a treat!  She is totally housetrained and has never had an accident in the house.  She is well behaved and has never been crated as there hasn't been a need to. She loves to go on walks and does not pull at all.  Started out on shorter walks with her and she does better than all of the foster's past foster dogs!  Underneath all Sasha's anxiety and fear is a sweet, gentle dog who will, over time, make someone a loving companion.
 
Sasha was recently accepted into a scholarship program for shy/fearful dogs. This consists of  having the opportunity to work virtually with a trainer and a veterinarian who specialize in dogs with fear and anxiety and also able to prescribe medications when necessary. Training will focus on positive reinforcement. 
The scholarship is for a certain number of sessions and she has a lot left – it doesn’t end on a certain date. This opportunity of support will continue into her new home to her new adopter, free of charge.

We have decided to try and find her forever home now for a few reasons.  The main reason is because we don’t want her to continue to have major improvements with her current foster only to have a huge setback when she is adopted.  Her improvements are coming quicker now so we think it would be a good time for her to find her new home.  

She also does not get along with one of our resident dogs.  We are not sure why it is only this dog as she ignores the other two, but we are concerned this could set her back some steps.  She has also become occasionally territorial of her space under one of the beds so we feel a change would benefit her. 

We believe Sasha will do best as an only dog in a quiet adult home with a very secure fenced yard so she has the option of relaxing outside for short periods of time on nice days – she would not do well on a tie-out.  Her new family should have experience with shy/fearful dogs and will need to be patient and understanding of her fears and anxiety and want to continue to work with her. She does have a lot of potential but it will take time.  She has started taking some anti-anxiety medications that she may or may not need long term.  

Sasha is spayed, up to date on vaccinations, and tested heartworm negative. Her microchip is registered to Second Chance. Before coming into our program, she had entropion surgery but, unfortunately, a little too much of her eyelid was removed - enough remains to cover the eye when she closes the lids so no artificial lubrication is needed.  If you have any question or would like to meet Sasha, call 651-771-5662.

animal.description:
Gorgeous George is an adorable 10 week old Golden/Shar Pei/Pit puppy.  He is currently 12 pounds and is an extremely loving, mellow puppy.  He loves playing with his dog housemates and gets along with all dogs he meets but has not been around cats.  He sleeps through the night in his crate and is working on his potty training.  He is super smart and picks up new training quickly.  

George also enjoys sitting on your lap and getting delicious rubs where he eventually falls asleep.  His foster family takes him in the car for school pick ups etc., and he loves the car and is very comfortable going to new stores and homes.

This guy will easily become the center of your world! He is intelligent, eager to please and a quick learner.  If you are looking for a sweet, fun, gorgeous puppy, George is the one!


Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY.  You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/).  All fields on the application must be completed.
Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit.   

Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application.  We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application.  If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. 

We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you.  We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. If you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) 

Thanks so much.

animal.description:
Hound lover, rejoice! 

This handsome, hunky hound is Quentyn. At 6 years old, this sweet, active, goofy guy has his sights set on a forever home. The kind of forever home where he can play the day away, curl up at a night, snuggle, and get loved on. Do you happen to be looking for a handsome hound? If so, read on!

Quentyn or ""Q"" as his foster Mom calls him was found running loose by a good samaritan. This poor guy was dirty, skinny, and shy when he was first found. It was clear he had been through a lot. However, with some tender loving care, this guy has not only put on weight but has also come way out of his shell. He is now an outgoing, playful guy. Quentyn needs an active family. One who likes long walks or playtime in the backyard. He would love, love, love a canine playmate, though it is not a requirement for his forever home. He loves other dogs, big and small! Any canine playmates should be active, too. Quentyn is currently fostering in New England with his foster Mom, human foster brother, and 2 canine foster siblings. He does great with his 7-year-old foster brother. He is very gentle and snuggly with him.

Quentyn's foster Mom describes him as ""goofy and clumsy."" He's one of those guys who doesn't have a sense of how big he is. AKA he's a 60 pound lap dog. He will climb over everything to perch himself right in his foster Mom's lap. At 60 pounds, this is no small feat! He is also described as a snuggle bug. When not playing, he wants all the love. He is also still working on mastering the dos and don't of indoor living. We are thinking he has never really lived in a home. When he first arrived, counters were free reign. So were all the other surfaces in the home. He has made great strides in learning his indoor manners but he will need continued work on this. He promises with time, patience, and cookies (this is a very important one), he will figure out the indoor rules.

Quentyn has been hard at work in his foster home working on potty training and crate training. He has just about mastered potty training. His foster Mom works from home so he is let out every 1-3 hours. With this routine, he is doing well. He will need a family who can carry on potty training. He whines and complains when he first goes into the crate. After some time, he settles in. He sleeps in the crate all night with no problem. 

Apply today to learn more about this hunky hound! Like, seriously, is he not a dream boat?!


Name: Quentyn
Breed: Hound mix
Sex: Male
Age: 6 years old
Weight: 59 pounds
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Vaccinations: Up to date
Heartworm: Negative 
Microchipped: Yes
Medical: Quentyn did have a malignent mass (mast cell tumor) that was removed when he was neutered. There is a chance that this mass could regrow. Currently there are no signs of regrowth or spread.

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS: 
Good with Children: Unknown
Good with Dogs: Yes- so far seems to be good with other dogs, mostly has interacted with dogs smaller than him.
Good with Cats: Unknown


Adoption Fee: $475.00


IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.

Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.

At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.


NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
Please, meet Zara.  She is a mix of Belgian shepherd dog, weight approximately 45 pounds, age 5-6 years.  Zara was rescued with newborn puppies from the industrial zone of the Moscow Region, Russia.  In December 2019, volunteers found her and took the emaciated and frozen Zara along with her were newborn puppies to a veterinary clinic that provides excellent care for rescue dogs.  The puppies were very weak and to the great grief all working to save them, the 8 puppies died.  But we managed to save Zara's life.  She is a very human-oriented dog of incredible kindness and affection who gets along well with other dogs, is neutral to cats, and good with children.  Zara walks easily on a leash, is microchipped, vaccinated, and healthy in relation to age.  Because she was a homeless street dog for some time, Zara’s teeth are worn, but our team obtained a dental examination where all diseased teeth were removed and all the rest were cleaned; her teeth and gums are now in excellent condition.  Let's help our “Black Beauty” find the best home and family!  The most loyal and best friends are those who have lived a hard life; they will appreciate and thank you for the rest of their days.  Don't be afraid to save; by saving those in need you are saving your soul.  God bless you!
 Regards Dire Straits Paws?

animal.description:
Yogi and Bear are on their way and will be available to meet Monday, Feb 1st. Please apply online.
Yogi is 4.5 yrs old, and weighs 16 lbs. 
Bear is 12.5 yrs old and weighs 60 lbs.
Adoption Coordinator:  LK
 

No, it’s not a mistake.  Bear, the Golden Mix and Yogi, the Chi mix, are a bonded pair so if you couldn’t decide between adopting a Chihuahua or a Golden Retriever, here is your chance to have both.  Bear is a wonderful “young man”.  He is 12 years young and weighs 60 pounds.  Bear has low energy and like a typical Retriever he loves bouncy balls and Yogi loves Bear so he also loves bouncy balls as well.  They are good around other dogs and children but have not been around cats so a cat free home would be best.  They both love to snuggle in big, soft, fluffy beds.  They are crate trained and should be crated together as Yogi needs Bear to be his pillow.  It is also Yogi’s job to keep Bear clean and will groom him like a cat.  Bear is a low maintenance, sweet, sweet boy.  He and Yogi are a bonded pair and must be adopted together. The adoption fee for the pair is $500.

Please complete an online APPLICATION if you wish to adopt.  Forever Home Rescue New England is a 501(c)3  non-profit organization. We are a network of foster homes in the South and the New England area. THERE IS NO SPECIFIC SHELTER LOCATION. If you wish to meet our dogs, you must first be approved by going through our application and screening process. Forever Home Rescue suggests obedience training for all puppies and dogs. All dogs are up to date on their shots, dewormed and spayed or neutered. Vet fees, transport fee and New England quarantine fees ARE INCLUDED in each dog's adoption fee. Also, any dogs older than pups--even if they are not marked housetrained in their posting---usually housetrain within a day or two, because most are used to living outside in the south and will prefer to do their business outdoors. Our dogs and pups are best suited for families with children 5 yrs old and up. If you are approved to adopt, please submit the $100 deposit by clicking on our rescue's name in this posting (Forever Home Rescue New England--in purple) which will bring you to a new page with the deposit link at the bottom.  STOP! If you have not been notified of your approval status do not make a deposit.

animal.description:
Fellow animal lovers, 
Allow us to introduce Logan. Logan is a ~1 yr old, neutered, male, German Shepherd / Rottie mix. Like many large dogs Logan's age, he looks like an adult, but is actually just a young lad - albeit a big one. PACC is supporting Logan's family, who have come to the difficult conclusion that they cannot provide Logan what he needs to be *his best self*. Simply put, Logan needs a more active home than the family can provide. A long walk (or run), a few tosses of the tennis ball and mental stimulation for those "smarter than the average bear's" and Logan will reach, and likely overtake, that *Good Boy* status. Adopters will benefit from the work Logan's family has put into his foundational skills. He is non-reactive to dogs on leash, relatively chill on even an overly busy coastal trail, good with kids, people (slightly more wary of men than women, but quickly warms up) and loves to PLAY. Can you say tennis ball?! Cause Logan can chase and return a tennis ball until the cows come home. He's also a big fan of the hose because it has, well...water!

If Logan sounds like a good fit with your family (great in a single or multiple dog household) please complete the PACC Adoption Application at the link below and we will reach out to you. Logan has not been kitty tested yet, but we can report back on that front if needed.

PACC Adoption Application:

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meatball is a 6 year old Cane Corso (Italian Mastiff) who came to us as an owner surrender. He is brand new to us so we are still getting to know him. He currently weighs 110 pounds and is said to be a retired service dog of some kind. He seems to be an easy going guy who kind of just rolls with the punches, so to speak. He has had basic training and is well mannered. He is incredibly strong and does need a little work on leash walking. Meatball will need to be neutered and his fee is $200.

BREED EXPERIENCE REQUIRED: Meatball is looking for an adopter who does have experience with Cane Corsos or similar breeds. He is not a dog for a first time dog owner. His former owner did say that he is NOT good with other dogs, which is known to typical of the breed. However, he has done well with cats and kids.

NOTE: We are closed to the public but are doing adoptions via private appointment once an application has been completed and approved. Applications can be submitted at our website, mchs.rescuegroups.org.

We are located at 101 22nd St. SE in Austin, right next to the airport. It's exit 180B off of I-90, right off of 218 South.

We do require that potential adopters be at least 21 years old and that any resident dogs be up to date on vaccinations, heartworm testing/preventative, and spayed or neutered.

animal.description:
Have you been looking for me? I hope so! My name is Remy, and I'm a mix of Staffordshire Terrier and Lab. Everybody loves a Lab, but they think Staffordshires aren't nice, and they confuse us with Pit Bulls (who can also be very nice). I'm a good boy! I'm cute, too! I am 1 1/2 years old and weigh about 60 pounds, all of which are filled with love. But my love may lead me to be too protective of you, so you will have to have a trainer to show me my mistake. Since I need to be the only dog in the house, that shouldn't be too hard for you. I love to walk, but I don't like collars. I pull on the leash partly due to that, and partly because I'm anxious to see other people and say Hi! I'm a real cuddler, but I need someone with dog experience to remind me who the boss is in case I'm cuddling too much, although I never heard of such a thing as cuddling too much, have you?? Have you been looking for me? Here I am! Right under your nose! (posted 9/4/20, HS) (revision 1/24/21)
**It is rare that we know with certainty the ages or mixes that make up our dogs, but we do our best to be as accurate as possible based upon our experience.
Adoption: $225.00The total fee for Remi, which includes adoption and transport, is only $225.00. This is not because there is anything wrong with him; we just want him in your home as soon as possible. 2/2/21 5:21 PM

animal.description:
Kiev is the sweetest boy! He is a 10 week old, 12lb Black Lab mix puppy that is curious about everything and has a very sweet disposition. We expect he will be 50-65 lbs when fully grown.  Above all, he loves to be with people and wants to be where he has a human to hang out with.  He’s happy to play, happy to nap, happy to snuggle and is a great companion for those of us working from home and looking for someone to nap at our feet!  He is great with kids of all ages, is very cute with other dogs (he just wants to lick them), has potty training almost mastered, and sleeps through the night!  He would be a great fit for most anyone who is able to keep him company during the day and is home or can take him with them - he will happily hop in the car too or go for long walks but just likes human companionship!


Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY.  You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/).  All fields on the application must be completed.
Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit.   

Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application.  We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application.  If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. 

We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you.  We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. Penny is a gorgeous 8 month old, 65 lb. Great Pyrenees/St. Bernard Mix.  Her sweet and sensitive eyes are quickly charming her foster family!  Penny is inquisitive, loveable, fluffy, and calm. Please call the shelter with questions, 319.753.8389... all animal inquiries must be made by telephone to the shelter during our hours listed below.  Thank you! 
****************
Introducing... Bobby! ?  This sweet boy came to us from Missouri in hopes of finding his perfect FOREVER home.  

Bobby (we've been calling him Bobby McGee because we love that song!) is a wonderful boy.  He was in a loving home with multiple other animals and at some point, there was a fight between him and a new dog brought into the home.  The family decided that Bobby would do better being rehomed than the new dog that had suffered abuse.  The rescue we received him from said that Bobby DID get along with male and female dogs, and that they tested him and he was even willing to share his food with a little Chihuahua.  Of course, a "meet and greet" would be required with any other dogs in a potential adopter's home.  We were also told that Bobby previously lived in a home with children present.  As he is new to DMCHS, we are currently unsure of how Bobby does with cats. 

Bobby is just 3 years old.  He is a 55-60lb pit mix (we also see lab and/or shepherd) in this gorgeous dog.  He is ridiculously sweet, loves attention, loves to play with toys, takes treats gently, and seems to know basic commands.... and he gives the best doggy kisses, ever.   Bobby does have skin allergies and a potential adopter would need to feed Bobby a good quality skin sensitivity food.  There is mention of a bit of separation anxiety so a family that is home a lot would be ideal for this gorgeous dog.  We are so excited to find a family for Bobby.....  This awesome boy is going to make a great family member for his new family!  ?

Interested? Please call us Tues-Fri from 3-6pm and from 1-5pm on the weekends.  319.753.8389.  Please remember that all visits to our shelter are currently by appointment only.  Thank you!


All dog adoptions include the spay/neuter, heartworm test, first two sets of basic immunizations as well as a rabies vaccine and a vet visit. Our adoption fee is $125.00 and all dogs do require an approved application.

animal.description:
Wilbur is a sweet large mixed breed dog that appears to be a labrador retriever. His estimated birthdate is 01/20/2014. He came to the Mission after spending 11 months in a local shelter and being overlooked for fear and kennel reactivity. 

Although we have only had him a short time, he has proven to be a normal and happy dog outside of the shelter setting. He is still on the fearful end of the spectrum and will take time to settle in with a new family. He appears to be potty trained and is also fine being crated for a full work day if needed. He also has excellent leash manners. 

Wilbur is good with other dogs and also seems tolerant of cats. Although he wouldn't be mean to children, his happiest life would likely be in a childless home because he prefers a quiet lifestyle without a ton of activity and unnecessary noise. He is currently extremely overweight and anyone interested in adopting him must be willing to adhere to his diet plan to help him get to a healthy pet to fit weight. We do not tolerate obesity in Mission pets as it leads to chronic pain and an overall lack of life quality and a decreased lifespan, so shedding those pounds will be paramount to his best future. 

Wilbur comes neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and dewormed, plus he will have a fresh dental cleaning. His adoption fee will be $200.00. To be considered to adopt, please visit www.murcismission.org and send in an application.

animal.description:
If you are interested in this dog, don't waste time with an inquiry! Fill out an application here to get the ball rolling...
https://pethavenmn.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/dog-adoption-application/

“Hello future cuddle mate(s),

Do you hear my lovely southern accent?  If you do not, foster mom rarely hears it since I rarely bark which makes her neighbors happy at her condo. It is hard to believe that I am a southern girl when I love playing in the snow. The ice, not so much.  

When I want to go outside, I will run to the door and back to you. I only had an accident when I got overly stimulated and forgot my manners. I do also enjoy a few walks each day.  

I hate crates and have broken out twice. Foster mom has started leaving me in her bedroom when she goes to work. I just sleep there until she comes home.

I love meeting new people and dogs. My eyesight has started to go so I cannot handle little kids anymore playing with me and around me. It makes me nervous. I also prefer to play with my toys solo. Somebody forgot to teach me how to share.  

I am an excellent, 16-pound cuddler, and love being pet and scratched behind the ears. I do not like being picked up and held. It does not matter if you were gone all day or gone five minutes, I will always greet you with wagging tail and jump up and down with my front legs in excitement. My human(s) are my world.  

Being an older lady (10 years old), I do have a couple things going on. I have a little bit of fur loss, and a couple bumps that the vet is looking into. Foster mom will tell you more.  

I would love to find a quiet household with human(s) who love to cuddle and will help me learn to share my toys. If you are ready for lots of love, please apply to learn more about me.

Queen Vivian"


Her adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm/Lyme test, all age-appropriate vaccinations (distemper, rabies, & Bordetella), HW and flea/tick preventative, and microchip implant and registration. 

There is no guarantee of age and breed as a rescue animal's history is unknown. All ages and breeds are best guess.

Adoption fees INCLUDE a mandatory sales tax of 7.525%.

Due to post-adoption services provided, it is Pet Haven's policy to only place dogs into homes within a 75-mile radius of the Minneapolis, MN city center.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Cash! My new friends at BAGSR say that my adopters will hit the jackpot with me. I am about 6 years old and have a beautiful, shinny black coat. Thankfully BAGSR grabbed me out of the shelter and found me a safe and loving foster home while they help me find a new family.  I'm a little underweight and should weigh about 80 pounds.  I have a healthy appetite though and will get there in no time. 

I've gotten quite used to indoor living and have even already learned how to use the dog door to go outside when I need to. My foster mom thinks I’m a pretty smart boy. I'm learning my basics here at my foster home and am a quick study. It would be great if my new family will take me to dog school to continue my learning. I'm sure I would love that.

I don’t love using a crate but sometimes I find treats in there so I may learn to like it!

I don’t need a ton of exercise but really enjoy leash walks. I’m quite polite on leash and I pass other dogs without issue. I just like to watch them go by.

I'm doing great with my foster dog siblings. With a dog/cat savvy owner who helps me, I may get along with a cat. I haven't been overyly interested in cats that I have met.

I take treats gently too.

I really enjoy affection as my foster mom is loving on me all of the time! I even make a little purring sound when I'm snuggling. I'm a vocal boy and like to moan and groan or let out a small bark when I want something.  I can be a little mouthy and do this little nibbly thing. My foster mom says that’s my way of showing affection. I didn't have much lovin' in my previous life but I do now and I will surely bond closely with my new people.

I'm very polite in the car and love to go. When my foster mom leaves me to run into a store or something, sometimes I bark once but then just wait patiently for her to come back. I am very attached to her and will bond closely with my new people.

I learned quickly what is expected of me in the house and have wonderful house manners. I can wait patiently at home with my foster dog siblings if my foster mom goes out and I also sleep quietly on my dog bed all through the night. 

I am still learning about toys and I find my hedgehog with a Christmas hat kind of fun to play with!

I’ll be waiting in Granite Bay. Hope to meet you!

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Thea. I'm a two and a half year old girl GSD. I have a beautiful soft long coat and I'm tall like a model and a fit 85 pounds. My coat will need good care - like lots of brushing to keep it silky and mat-free. I really enjoy being brushed!

I am looking for a family who can spend time with me doing the fun things that we youngsters so enjoy. I'll need an active family as I need regular physical and mental exercise to keep me healthy. I would love to continue my training as I'm super smart but I really need you to be a leader and make sure I do everything right. If you don't tell me I will try to figure it out myself and I don't always get it right. I love long walks, hikes, road trips and time at the beach. I really enjoy water! Exercise and the outdoors are really fun for me. I'm also treat motivated and take treats gently. When I'm really excited, I can be a little too mouthy and will need to be reminded to keep it soft. I just can't help myself sometimes but I'm working on it. 

Did I mention I love car rides. Oh boy, I love getting in the car and going places and I am a good backseat rider. I'm not a fan of being left alone for too long as I really would prefer to be with my person. I will need a family where someone is home a lot but can help me learn to be without you. I am crate trained but it's not my favorite place to be. 

I'll be a super fun companion for an active adopter who has lots of time to spend with me. I get lots of attention when out and about and meet strangers well. I'm good with other dogs, too but no cats for me please. They really annoy me. I do forget my manners when on leash and will pull a little more than most people like. I've been learning to walk on a front clip harness and I'm doing pretty well. I can also walk with a head halter but prefer the front clip harness as I love to sniff my way through my walks. Maybe some fun "hide the treats" games would be good!!  I'm up for just about anything.....

I'll be waiting in Windsor for my perfect match.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Master Beckley (or 'Beck' as he is fondly called by his foster family) is a 4-yr old small Wire Terrier mix, possibly some Jack Russell.
Beck is a sort of 'special needs' boy, as he was born with luxating patellas on both of his hind legs. What this means is that he walks like a 'crab' on his hind legs - so, he definitely has a "unique" gait. But, this does not slow him down at all. He runs and plays and does just fine. As he gets older, he will likely develop arthritis in his rear legs sooner than a dog without this condition.
This being said, Beck is a very sweet, happy and lovable boy. He particularly loves women. With men, it can take him some time to warm up to them, but it really depends. In his original foster home, he was fine with his foster dad (who is 69), but Beck seems to have a trust problem with younger males.
As noted, Beckley adores women, and, as you can see in some of his pictures, he loves his sweaters. He actually prefers to wear outfits as not!!! He sleeps with his foster Grandmother and gets along well with the other dogs in the house (a Cattle Dog and a very large English Bulldog/Am. Staff Terrier).
Beck is about 90% house trained, as the cold weather/snow is hard on him to go outside. However, his foster Mom does make sure he goes out on a regular basis.
Beck is a wonderful little man who needs a person who is willing to dote on him and love him for who the sweet, affectionate little guy that he is. We believe he would do best in a household with women only, or an older couple. Please consider making this sweet boy become a cherished member of your home.
If you have the time, willingness and ability to provide a loving, nurturing home to Beckley for his whole life, we'd love to hear from you. To pursue Beckley's adoption, you will need to register on www.safeatlast.net. (Click Register on the left-hand side of our homepage.) When you receive your password, please log back on to our website to complete the Safe at Last online adoption application. (Click Forms/Applications on the left-hand side of our home page.) Once we have your application, if we feel your home is a good match for Beckley, we will contact you by email to schedule the phone interview to commence the review process. Our process is very straightforward but does involve the phone interview, reference checks and a home assessment. An adoption fee of $425 also applies.
Please be advised that you cannot meet Beckley until you have been approved to adopt. We cannot consider you until you have submitted the completed Safe at Last online adoption application. Delay in submitting your application will put you at a disadvantage to other potentially qualified applicants.
Finally, Beckley is being fostered in the Oneonta/Morris NY area. Approved adopters are required to go to the foster home to complete the adoption. Adopters are also required to adhere to all COVID-19 safety protocols (including mask) when at the foster home.
Thank you for your interest in this sweet boy!
NY Rescue Registry No. RR 087.

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Buddy!

I am a big, oversized puppy and I love, love, love every person I’ve ever met. I’m a pretty big boy (70 pounds and growing) and I’m still learning how to control my floppy puppy body. I fall over and run into things a lot, but my foster mom and dad think it’s really cute and funny! Even though I’m a big boy, I think I’m the perfect size lap dog and love to lay on you, sit on you and snuggle and give you kisses non-stop.

My foster mom says I’m really smart. I didn’t have many rules before I came to her house, but I’ve already learned sit, paw and down. I also sit and wait to eat my meals every day because I’m a very polite boy!

I’m a PRO at potty training. I learned REALLY fast!!! I was a super nervous about my crate when I first came to live with my foster mom, but it’s just because I prefer to be right next to humans instead! I’m getting better with my crate every day and now sleep in my crate all through the night without crying.

I live with two dogs in my foster home and I LOVE them, but I’m still learning some manners, so you may need to be patient with me. I’m perfectly fine being your only Buddy, but if I have a dog sibling, they need to be tolerant and willing to help me learn how to play without getting too excited.

Thanks for reading about me, I can’t wait to meet you and see if I can be your best “Buddy” for life!

heck out this handsome dude - this is Magnum !!
Magnum is a young (1.5 years old) guy, he has a lot of puppy enthusiasm and eagerness to please. Magnum has been taught to sit when asked and with some training and patience he will certainly learn more commands.  He is playful too and enjoys being loved up.  
Magnum's ideal family will be willing to provide him a structured home, where he can continue to learn good manners and build a solid trusting relationship with his family.  Adopters with German Shepard experience are preferred. At this time, Magnum will need to be the only pet in his new home.  Due to his energy level, tendency to jump up looking for attention, and leash manners, we recommend any children in his forever home are teenagers.  
Breed experience preferred.

animal.description:
All people inquiring about pets listed as Courtesy Listings on the EAPL website and/or EAPL posting adoption boards should contact the current pet owner/rescue/shelter for answers to any questions and for final approval and placement. Please DO NOT CONTACT EAPL about courtesy listings. The pet owner/rescue/shelter and new owner shall make all arrangements on transferring the pet, information on history, vaccines, etc.

Name: Buddy (also answers to Butters) Age: ~10 Weight: 90 pounds

Color: Brown with a few white spots Gets along with: All adults and older children (10+)

Contact: 720-985-7018 or AdoptSweetBuddy@gmail.com

Buddy couldn't be a sweeter dog! He's older but has a lot of life left in him. He loves going on walks, running like a goof around the yard, and naps! The perfect home for Buddy is where he can nap, relax, and get pets. He needs to be the only pet in the home and any children need to be over 10. He is very friendly with everyone he meets but doesn't like kids climbing on him so he would be best in a home with older or no children. He loves sleeping in the sun and will follow it around the house throughout the day or lay outside in it when it's warm out. He LOVES a nice comfy dog bed but is just as happy to lay on blankets or a pile of laundry. Buddy is crate trained and can hang in his crate when you're away during the day or be left out, he'll just take naps the whole time. He likes stuffed toys and soft rubber ones, he is missing some teeth so he doesn't chew through them very quickly. He also loves all treats and will gladly eat medicine if you put it in some American cheese. He will follow you around the house because he loves being near people. Buddy is scared of fireworks and loud noises, creating a place for him to hide when that's happening really helps him. It's best if he gets to go outside to potty before fireworks start. He is also scared of any size vacuum and will run away from them. He is food motivated and has puppy dog eyes down! He'll eat any kind of treat and will love you for it! He's a great dog and deserves a great home!
animal.name: Buddy Courtesy Listing
